I remenber John a fellow machine gunner in Vietnam who once told me, &quot;For those who have fought for it, Life has a flavour the protected will never know. <br>
For the first time in 30 years, 12 of us from our platoon in Viet Nam gathered in February of this year. Three of the local newspapers did a story of that reunion as we had not seen or had spoken to each other or other Marines in all that time. It was one of the most memorable events in my life. Within moments of our reunion we had captured that same trust, friendship and unit integrity we had enjoyed 30 years before in the land of no postage stamps. I too enjoyed the Desert Storm situation as it developed. I believe that was the turning point for the healing of that many Viet Nam vets needed to see. America pride in defeating a worthy foe where the enemy was clearly defined. Many never understood and still do not understand that who we fought in Viet Nam was not the local Viet Cong but a well trained and discipline foreign invader from the North. Individuals that had been trained and supplied by the Soviet Union and Communist China. Hanoi is just now, beginning to admit that they had Chinese and Russian advisors serving and advising them in the South .<br>
